##### groovvy code which can be use in jenkins

1. Standardized Slack Notification (vars/sendSlack.groovy)
Instead of writing complex JSON for every build, use this to send consistent alerts.
groovy
// vars/sendSlack.groovy
def call(String buildStatus) {
    def color = (buildStatus == 'SUCCESS') ? 'good' : 'danger'
    def message = "${buildStatus}: Job '${env.JOB_NAME}' [build #${env.BUILD_NUMBER}] (${env.BUILD_URL})"
    
    slackSend(color: color, message: message)
}
Use code with caution.

How to use it in your Jenkinsfile:
groovy
post {
    always {
        sendSlack(currentBuild.currentResult)
    }
}
Use code with caution.

2. Docker Build & Push (vars/dockerBuild.groovy)
This script automates tagging your images with the build number and pushing them to a registry (like Docker Hub or ACR).
groovy
// vars/dockerBuild.groovy
def call(Map config = [:]) {
    def imageName = config.imageName
    def registry = config.registry ?: "my-default-registry.com"
    def tag = "${env.BUILD_NUMBER}"

    echo "Building image: ${imageName}:${tag}"
    
    sh "docker build -t ${registry}/${imageName}:${tag} ."
    
    withCredentials([usernamePassword(credentialsId: 'docker-creds', passwordVariable: 'PASS', usernameVariable: 'USER')]) {
        sh "echo $PASS | docker login ${registry} -u $USER --password-stdin"
        sh "docker push ${registry}/${imageName}:${tag}"
    }
}
Use code with caution.

How to use it in your Jenkinsfile:
groovy
stage('Build Image') {
    steps {
        dockerBuild(imageName: 'my-app', registry: 'myrepo.azurecr.io')
    }
}
Use code with caution.

3. Cleanup Workspace (vars/cleanEnv.groovy)
A helper to ensure your build agent stays clean, avoiding "disk full" errors.
groovy
// vars/cleanEnv.groovy
def call() {
    echo "Cleaning up workspace and old Docker images..."
    deleteDir() // Deletes the current workspace
    sh "docker image prune -f --filter 'until=24h'" // Deletes old dangling images
}


